y of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Washburn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Washburn","meanings":["English: habitational name from Great and Little Washbourne (Gloucestershire), or Washbourne in Halwell (Devon). The Gloucestershire placename derives from Old English <i>wæsse</i> (genitive <i>wæssan</i>) ‘wet place, swamp, marsh’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’. The Devon placename derives from Old English <i>wæsce</i> ‘place for washing’ + <i>burna</i>.","History: John Washburn came to MA in 1626 and settled in Duxbury, MA, in 1632."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Washburne was born in 1550, in Wichenford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Anthony Washburne, was 29 and his mother, Anne Reade, was 21. He married Mary Heriot in 1571. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in June 1634, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 84, and was buried in City of London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"155